The HashMap Recognition Rule
Before thinking about code, ask yourself:

      "Am I repeatedly searching for something I've already seen?"

If the answer is yes, a HashMap or HashSet is often the right tool.

===============================================================================================================================================================================

HashMap vs HashSet

              This is a favorite Google follow-up.

| HashMap                                                                  | HashSet                                         |
| ------------------------------------------------------------------------ | ----------------------------------------------- |
| Stores key-value pairs                                                   | Stores only unique values                       |
| Use when you need associated information (index, count, frequency, etc.) | Use when you only care whether something exists |
| Example: Two Sum                                                         | Example: Contains Duplicate                     |



Interview Question:        When would you choose HashSet over HashMap?

Good answer:      "If I only need to know whether an element has been seen before, a HashSet is sufficient. 
                    If I need additional information such as an index or frequency, I would use a HashMap."

