Problem 1 – Contains Duplicate

Problem :          nums = [1,2,3,1]

Return :            true

because  1    appears twice.




===============================================================================================================================================================================

First Question   How would you solve this without a HashSet?

Most people answer:   Compare every element  with every other element.

Complexity?  O(n²)

===================
Can We Do Better?   Think.

While scanning the array,  suppose you are currently at:   3

Wouldn't it be useful if you already knew whether   3    had appeared before?

Exactly.      That's a HashSet.

SOLUTION :
          HashSet<Integer> seen = new HashSet<>();          
          for each number          
              if already present          
                   return true          
              else          
                   store it          
          return false

JAVA:

          public boolean containsDuplicate(int[] nums) {          
              Set<Integer> seen = new HashSet<>();          
              for (int num : nums) {          
                  if (seen.contains(num)) {
                      return true;
                  }          
                  seen.add(num);
              }          
              return false;
          }

Complexity  Time :  O(n)
            Space: O(n)


===============================================================================================================================================================================

nterview Follow-up   :       Why not use a HashMap?

Excellent question.

                  Because we don't need
                  
                  1 → index                  
                  or                  
                  1 → count
                  
                  We only need Does 1 exist?

                A HashSet already answers that.

