One Suggestion That Will Make a Huge Difference

From tomorrow onward, whenever I ask a coding question, don't write code first.

I want you to answer in this exact format:

Interviewer: "Solve Two Sum."

You:

Clarifying Questions
            Is there exactly one solution?
            Can numbers be negative?
            Should I return indices or values?
Brute-force Approach
            Explain it.
State complexity.
            Observation
            "We're repeatedly searching for previously seen values."
Optimal Approach
Explain the algorithm.
Justify the data structure.
Complexity
            Time.
            Space.
Edge Cases
            Duplicates.
            Empty input.
            Single element.
            All elements equal.
Only then write the code.

If you consistently follow this structure, by the time we reach mock interviews, you'll already be communicating like an experienced L5 candidate rather than simply solving coding problems.




